<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="485" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,258,1183]" box="[199,1146,1050,1075]" pageId="12" pageNumber="485">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1050,1075]" pageId="12" pageNumber="485">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name refers to the lobed dark medial marking of the crown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,258,1183]" pageId="12" pageNumber="485">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,273,1086,1111]" pageId="12" pageNumber="485">Notes.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich &amp; Zahniser" authorityYear="2019" box="[544,706,1086,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Makilingia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="485" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="davaoensis">
<emphasis box="[544,706,1086,1110]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="485">M. davaoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in coloration but differs in having the lateral lobes of the median black marking on the crown extended to the lateral margin, the distal unpigmented section of the male subgenital plate well developed and the aedeagus with two pairs of acute atrial processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
